<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-316-251  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 316 251.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEE Proceedings Part E Computers and Digital Techniques  January1989 v136 n1 p9(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Static interconnection network extensibility based on marginalperformance-cost analysis. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dowd, P.W.; Dowd, M.; Jabbour, K.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The paper examines the trade-off between cost and performance of ahypercube based computer interconnection network founded on adetailed cost analysis model.andP;  A cost function is proposed whichconsiders the economies of scale of bandwidth available throughoptical fibre communication and the nonincremental increase innode complexity resulting from variations in network size.andP;  Whenconsidering topology choice, an important consideration isexpansion.andP;  Any comparison of expansion should be done throughmarginal analysis: weighing the additional benefits (performance)against the additional cost resulting from expansion.andP;  Todemonstrate this technique, four interconnection networks areconsidered: boolean n-cube, nearest neighbor mesh hypercube,generalised hypercube, and spanning multiaccess channel hypercube.andO;Systems with equalised performance are studied, investigating thevariations in cost.andP;  This permits the investigation of thetrade-off of performance-cost between high capacity communicationchannels and increased number of channels and degree.andP;  (Reprintedby permission of the publisher)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Distributed SystemsNetworksPerformance-Cost RelationshipStatic SystemsBandwidthFiber OpticsConnectivityCost Benefit Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   Topology characteristic summary. (table)Hypercube topologies. (chart)Node model, with three forms of local interconnection. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>